{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close",
    "objective": "To demonstrate the ability to link a statutory legal requirement with its corresponding non-statutory technical guidance in a real-world installation scenario.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In the electrical industry, statutory and non-statutory documents work together. The statutory regulations set the legal 'must'—the mandatory safety outcomes required by law. The non-statutory regulations provide the technical 'how'—the industry-approved methods and standards used to achieve those legal outcomes.",
      "For example, a contractor must ensure an installation is safe to satisfy the law, but they look to the industry standards to find the specific measurements and methods to make it so."
    ],
    "questionText": "You are planning a new installation. You must ensure the work complies with the Electricity at Work Regulations (EAWR) and the Requirements for Electrical Installations (BS 7671). Classify both documents as either statutory or non-statutory, and identify which one provides the technical guidance used to prove you have met the legal requirements of the other.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "EAWR is statutory; BS 7671 is non-statutory. BS 7671 provides the technical guidance to meet the legal requirements of the EAWR.",
      "Electricity at Work Regulations: Statutory. BS 7671: Non-statutory. Following BS 7671 is the way to show compliance with the statutory EAWR."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about which document is a law passed by Parliament and which one is the 'Big Blue Book' of technical rules."
  }
}

